1 General Information

There were two runs that went into BioProject PRJNA1111477. This file is for processing files in Run 2, aka the large run in which most of the samples were run.

1.0.1 Info for data analysis

For the lung tissue samples, primer sequences have been removed. However, for fecal samples, they will have to be removed.

1.0.2 Database

Im using Silva version 138 with training data formatted for DADA2 from https://zenodo.org/record/3731176#.ZElLBnbMKUl.

1.0.3 Codes

Please note that many of the coding lines below are from Dr.Callahans DADA2 tutorial.

1.0.4 Data availability

For reproducibility, this file assumes that you have download the files from BioProject PRJNA1111477 of NCBI SRA database in .fastq format. There should be 293 SRR files under that BioProject. For convenience, I have also downloaded the metadata to convert SRR names to sample names.

Check that primers are removed:

FWD <- "GTGYCAGCMGCCGCGGTAA"   # full primer seq TCGTCGGCAGCGTCAGATGTGTATAAGAGACAGGTGYCAGCMGCCGCGGTAA  515F
REV <- "GGACTACNVGGGTWTCTAAT"  # full primre seq GTCTCGTGGGCTCGGAGATGTGTATAAGAGACAGGGACTACNVGGGTWTCTAAT 806rB

allOrients <- function(primer) {
    # Create all orientations of the input sequence
    require(Biostrings)
    dna <- DNAString(primer)  # The Biostrings works w/ DNAString objects rather than character vectors
    orients <- c(Forward = dna, Complement = complement(dna), Reverse = reverse(dna), 
        RevComp = reverseComplement(dna))
    return(sapply(orients, toString))  # Convert back to character vector
}
FWD.orients <- allOrients(FWD)
REV.orients <- allOrients(REV)

primerHits <- function(primer, fn) {
    # Counts number of reads in which the primer is found
    nhits <- vcountPattern(primer, sread(readFastq(fn)), fixed = FALSE)
    return(sum(nhits > 0))
}

rbind(FWD.ForwardReads = sapply(FWD.orients, primerHits, fn = filtFs_Fecal[[1]]), 
    FWD.ReverseReads = sapply(FWD.orients, primerHits, fn = filtRs_Fecal[[1]]), 
    REV.ForwardReads = sapply(REV.orients, primerHits, fn = filtFs_Fecal[[1]]), 
    REV.ReverseReads = sapply(REV.orients, primerHits, fn = filtRs_Fecal[[1]]))

5.8 Check: sequence lengths

With the primers removed, the target amplicon region should be about 254 bp. Lets check:

seqtab <- makeSequenceTable(mergers)
table(nchar(getSequences(seqtab)))
## 
##  215  233  234  235  251  252  253  254  255  256  257  258  273  274  285  311 
##    1    1   18   61    2  199 2276 3765   60   17    2    1    1    1    1    2 
##  322  425 
##    1    1

They indeed peak at the expected length. Remove sequences that are unexpectedly long or short:

seqtab2 <- seqtab[,nchar(colnames(seqtab)) %in% 250:256]

5.9 Chimera Removal

seqtab.nochim <- removeBimeraDenovo(seqtab2, method="consensus", minFoldParentOverAbundance = 4, multithread=TRUE, verbose=TRUE)
## Identified 3014 bimeras out of 6319 input sequences.
dim(seqtab.nochim)
## [1]  280 3305
sum(seqtab.nochim)/sum(seqtab2)
## [1] 0.9366782

While there are a good number of bimeras, they accounted for less than 7% of the reads.

5.11 Save and export as phyloseq object

otus = otu_table(seqtab.nochim, taxa_are_rows=FALSE)
sd = sample_data(meta.df)
ps <- phyloseq(otus,
               sd,
               tax_table(taxa))
dna <- Biostrings::DNAStringSet(taxa_names(ps))
names(dna) <- taxa_names(ps)
ps <- merge_phyloseq(ps, dna)
taxa_names(ps) <- paste0("ASV", seq(ntaxa(ps))) # Give taxa ASV names for easier graphing 
ps
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object

ps.rds = file.path(git.dir, paste0("ps.Run2.rds"))
